{answers": {"email_8765490": null, "email_9107531": null, "yesno_8163475": "0", "rating_9045688": "1", "yesno_10176601": "0", "dropdown_7603830": "Economics", "dropdown_9077980": null, "textarea_7603814": null, "textarea_10173448": "Ian.Driscoll@amcham-shanghai.org Nearly one-third of U.S. companies (29 percent) reported that China is their number one global investment priority  a record high. Almost all companies surveyed  96 percent  reported they had maintained or increased investment levels in China operations for 2014, with the same number forecasting a similar investment intent for 2015.
 
More companies are at the low to moderate end of planned investment increases for 2015, with 41 percent indicating increases in the 1 to 15 percent range, and 21 percent planning increases of 16 to 50 percent. These numbers reflect a shift to the lower end of investment levels, with a steady decline over the past five years in the number of companies planning high investment increases.
 
For the small number of companies planning to decrease their investment in 2015 (4.4 percent), the reasons given are rising costs and expectations of slower growth in China.
 
In China for China Strategy
 
For U.S. businesses the shift towards an in China, for China strategy strengthened, indicating a confidence in future market opportunities. A record 67 percent reported that their companys number one priority is to produce or source goods or services in China for the China market. Conversely, a strategy and business line focused on manufacturing and production in China for the U.S. and other markets continued to decline, a reflection of both the changing nature of U.S. business operations in China and its high-cost environment.
 
Optimism High But Signs of a Shift
 
An optimistic or slightly optimistic five-year outlook characterized 85 percent of all companies, reflecting a continued sense of confidence in the business opportunities in China. We have reported high levels of optimism for many years.
 
There was, however, a notable shift in the degree of optimism. Those in the optimistic category dropped 10 percentage points (from 53 to 43 percent) and those in the less exuberant slightly optimistic category increased 9 percentage points (from 33 to 42 percent). There was also a slight uptick in the neutral response. This tempering of outlook reflects a business community that is sensitive to Chinas forecast for decreased growth and must deal with the challenges of high costs, increasing competition and regulatory ambiguity.", "textfield_9116414": null, "fileupload_7219011": null, "list_6462402_other": null, "list_9115461_other": null, "textfield_10176495": null, "textfield_10176836": null, "list_6462400_choice": "Important. We also recently achieved an important marketing milestone, in which our online marketing efforts pay for themselves on the same day.

Our vision for the future is that rather than running 22 searches per trip, customers will run 0. Artificial intelligence technology will notify travelers automatically of the best travel options for their upcoming trips. Through these one-to-one customer relationships, suppliers will be able to bypass Google and other intermediaries, and reach customers with the best offers directly. We have already launched a version of this technology called Hello Hipmunk.

We are in partnership discussions with a number of large international travel companies, and I wanted to check in with you as well.

I'm going to be in Chicago next Friday, January 15th, and would appreciate the chance to meet. If you're not around then, please let me know your availability for a call on Monday, January 18th.

Thanks.

-Adam Goldstein
